   Who's News:
   Citizens Utilities Picks
   Tow for Top 2 Posts
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS CTY CITUA
</CO>
<LP>
   STAMFORD, CONN. -- Citizens Utilities Co. named Leonard
Tow, a cable television and cellular telephone executive,
chairman and chief executive of the utility and
telecommunications company.
   As chairman, Mr. Tow fills a position vacant since last
year. As chief executive, he succeeds Ishier Jacobson, who
retires June 30.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Tow, 60 years old, will continue as chairman and chief
executive of Century Communications Corp., New Canaan, Conn.,
which owns about 2.2% of the Series A common shares of
Citizens Utilities.
   Mr. Tow, who has been a director of Citizens for almost 15
months, said the two companies are "not linked from a
standpoint of operations, but there is an interest in the
field of cellular telephones." Asked how Mr. Tow will be able
to run both companies, a spokeswoman said: "Management teams
at both companies are very strong; they will run day-to-day
operations."
   As previously announced, Daryl A. Ferguson, 51, senior
vice president of operations and engineering, succeeds Mr.
Jacobson, 68, as president of Citizens. Mr. Ferguson was also
named chief operating officer, effective July 1.
