<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   An Un-Trendy Sears?
   Totally Awesome
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<CO>
   S
</CO>
<IN>
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   Your May 9 page-one article "Fashion Statement" provided
this old Sears veteran a rare insight into the latest scheme
to achieve a trendier image for the giant retailer.
   But I think you may have been misled into thinking
something new is happening across the aisle from the paint
cans and manure spreaders. I remember very well before my
retirement three years ago that the same blandishments wafted
reassuringly from the lips of a parade of successive senior
managers and fashion consultants. Can it indeed be possible
to reinvent the wheel?
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. ever decides to stick with any
strategy long enough to see it work, the power of that
venerable merchandising organization will be awesome. But in
fact, Sears has tinkered with so many, often-conflicting,
strategies since the early 1970s (and earlier) that it should
come as no surprise that it is struggling in today's hostile
competitive environment.
   Lloyd S. VanSchoyck
   Palm Harbor, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0082
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900626-0082.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Pulitzer Keeps Track
   Of What's on the Boards
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<LP>
   Edwin Wilson is, of course, correct in noting that the
production each year of 200 new plays at theaters all across
the U.S. makes the task of Pulitzer Prize drama jurors a
difficult one ("Good Regional Play Points Up Bad Pulitzer
Problem," Leisure &amp; Arts, June 14). Like Mr. Wilson, the
Pulitzer Prize Board is keenly aware of this situation and
continually seeks ways to ensure that regional theater is
covered as thoroughly as possible. For some years now it has
encouraged its drama jurors to travel at board expense to
regional theaters that appear to have particularly promising
offerings. And this year, in keeping with a decision taken
last November, it has increased the number of drama jurors
from three to five in order to make possible a broader
geographic representation.
   Between these measures and the fact that as professional
critics our drama jurors can reasonably be presumed to be
aware of what is going on at theaters in their various
regions of the country, I would submit that the Pulitzer
selection system is a good deal more equitable and
comprehensive than Mr. Wilson recognizes.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Robert C. Christopher
   Administrator
   The Pulitzer Prizes
   Columbia University
   New York
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0081
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900626-0081.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canadian Markets
   Rebound After
   Initial Sell-Off
   ----
   By Larry M. Greenberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Canadian financial markets recovered from an
initial sell-off yesterday following the demise of the Meech
Lake constitutional accord.
   Analysts said a rebound in the Canadian dollar triggered a
positive response in the bond and equity markets. They
predicted that Canada's relatively attractive interest-rate
yields will continue to support the Canadian dollar in coming
weeks, overriding lingering anxieties about the future of the
Canadian union.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The wide interest-rate spreads {between Canada and the
U.S.} look ever more attractive now that the Canadian debate
about the Meech Lake accord has gone out of the air," said
Edward Carmichael, an economist at Burns Fry Ltd. in Toronto.
   The Meech Lake accord, aimed at meeting demands of mostly
French-speaking Quebec and defusing independence forces in
the province, failed over the weekend after two provincial
legislatures adjourned without ratifying the proposed
constitutional amendment.
   Yesterday, Montreal was a sea of blue-and-white Quebec
flags as a good-natured crowd of about 200,000 watched a
parade marking St. Jean Baptiste Day, the French-speaking
province's "national" holiday. Lined up 10 deep in places
along the three-mile route, Montrealers smiled and waved and
at times chanted, "We want a country. We want a country."
   Canadian market sentiment was boosted by a report that
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. affirmed its Triple-A rating on
Canadian government debt and Double-A-minus rating on
Quebec's debt. Moody's Investors Service Inc. also said it
would maintain its Double-A-3 rating on Quebec debt.
   But Standard &amp; Poor's said it changed its outlook for
Quebec's long-term debt to "developing" from "positive"
because of political uncertainty. "While S&amp;P expects no
change in the relationship between Quebec and Canada in the
near term, ongoing discussions of constitutional reform could
become increasingly divisive," the rating agency said.
   The Canadian dollar began the trading day in Asia, falling
swiftly to 84.20 cents from 84.85 cents late Friday in
Toronto. But it ended higher at 84.95 cents.
   The Canadian 20-year bellwether bond ended down 1/2 point,
or 50 Canadian dollars lower for every C$1,000 face amount,
to 10.62%. But with U.S. bonds also falling, the Canadian
issue improved against its American counterpart, narrowing
its premium over the U.S. 30-year bellwether bond to 206
basis points from 209 basis points on Friday. A basis point
is a hundredth of a percentage point.
   Canadian equities also declined but by little more than
the U.S. stocks measured by the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
The Toronto Stock Exchange 300-composite index lost 16.56
points to 3474.16 points. Volume was light at 15.5 million
shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
