<HL>
   Southern Co. Says
   Dispute Settled
   For $300 Million
   ----
   By Glenn Ruffenach
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   GSU SO
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- Southern Co. said its subsidiaries will receive
about $300 million, before taxes, in a settlement with Gulf
States Utilities Co. over disputed power sales contracts.
   Southern Co., the giant utility holding company, said the
proposed settlement will be made in the form of a financial
package, including cash, common stock and deferred payments.
The company said it couldn't estimate the effect on earnings.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Gulf States, based in Beaumont, Texas, said the settlement
was in the best interests of its shareholders. The
four-year-old dispute "was like a dark cloud hanging over us,
preventing us from looking into the future," a spokeswoman
said.
   Gulf States said its cash outlay would total $167 million.
Of the remaining $133 million, $68 million is in an escrow
account, and the balance will be paid in the form of six
million new shares of Gulf States common stock.
   The spokeswoman for Gulf States said the company expects
to take an after-tax charge to net income of between $110
million and $115 million in 1990. In 1989, Gulf States posted
a loss of $45.5 million, or $1 a share, on revenue of $1.6
billion.
   The dispute began in July 1986. Gulf States, which had
contracted to buy approximately $1 billion in electricity
from Southern Co. over a 10-year period beginning in 1982,
asked Southern Co. to consider renegotiating the contracts
because energy demands had fallen below predicted levels.
When Southern Co. declined, Gulf States filed suit in U.S.
District Court in Beaumont. Southern Co. countersued in
December 1988.
   No hearings had been scheduled for the suits. Both cases
were still in discovery.
   Southern Co.'s president, Edward L. Addison, said in a
statement, "We're pleased that we've been able to resolve
this contract dispute in out-of-court negotiations and come
to terms that protect the long-term interests of our
companies."
   As collateral for future payments, Gulf States said it
will pledge the Lewis Creek Generating Plant, a 520-megawatt
gas-fired facility near Willis, Texas. Gulf States will also
provide Southern Co. with transmission access to the plant at
a rate approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
   The settlement is subject to several contingencies,
including approval by the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission and the Securities and Exchange Commission.
Southern Co. said the settlement will terminate the contracts
and end litigation between the parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0076
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900626-0076.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   The Tax Burden Builds
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<LP>
   We hope someone in the Bush White House is supposed to
keep an eye on budget politics beyond the Beltway. While Mr.
Bush's no-new-taxes pledge still stands as a robust political
strategy, some big-state electorates -- California, New York,
New Jersey -- are encountering the kinds of solutions that
politicians devise to address the universal phenomenon of a
bloated public sector: Increase the tax burden. If the White
House miscalculates the terms of a budget deal with Congress,
it may antagonize voters already steamed up at the economic
policies of their own states.
   In California, a July 1 budget deadline is causing a
meltdown over deficits. The Republican Governor is a lame
duck, and a Democratic legislature must lead in choosing
between taxes and spending.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A conference committee in Sacramento has begun searching
for a way to make the revenue-growth line as steep as the
expenditure track, which right now has been spotted a $2.9
billion lead for next fiscal year. The Democratic leadership
insists that categories such as welfare have to keep rolling
along at double-digit yearly rates of increase.
   Two leading Democrats in the legislature have boldly
spelled out plans for a $2.3 billion tax hike. Half the
revenues would come from increasing the top personal income
tax rate back to 11%, where it was before the state conformed
to federal tax revision and eliminated many deductions in
return for a 9.3% ceiling on rates. This higher bracket would
cover income from all sources that exceeds $100,000 for an
individual, $200,000 for a joint return.
   Meanwhile, in New Jersey, Democratic Governor Jim Florio
has steamrollered his own tax increase through the
legislature. Under newspaper headlines this past weekend
proclaiming "State's biggest tax hike," stories described a
$2.8 billion tax package. Taxes will go up on individuals
with incomes above $35,000 and couples above $70,000. The
highest tax bracket will be doubled to 7%. A higher sales tax
of 7% will now extend to a wide range of previously untaxed
items and services. (Part of the proposal includes plans to
offer property-tax relief to some people.)
   During the Reagan years, one of the rationales for cutting
taxes and tax rates was to create economic incentives for
individuals to work harder or more innovatively; in return,
government wouldn't claim such a large share of the new,
additional dollars. It is intriguing to compare this
philosophy with what is driving these state efforts.
   In California, Johan Klehs, who heads the Assembly's tax
committee and is one of the sponsors of the new tax plan,
happens to have supported the 1987 rate reductions in
California. He and other Democrats liked the primary effect
of those changes: to cut the tax burden for low-income
residents. Moreover, they were projected to increase the
taxes paid by the rich. And indeed, they apparently did just
that. Mr. Klehs admits, "Actually, personal income tax
revenues have done quite well."
   Now, having defoliated many of the tax havens, Mr. Klehs &amp;
Co. want to expose the high-income-earners to the old steeper
rate. History suggests they won't get as much revenue as they
think from this ploy, as creative tax attorneys find new
loopholes. But this kind of bait-and-switch politics may also
poison future attempts to broaden tax bases and reduce rates,
a trend that economists across the political spectrum have
encouraged because it reduces the distortions of the tax
code. California's tax boosters also have in mind a rise in
business taxes to 9.6%, where the rate was before the 1987
changes. The state's Democrats point to unpopular spending
cuts as the alternative.
   In New Jersey, much of the money collected annually from
the higher income taxes will be redistributed through a
complex formula among city school systems that the Governor
believes operate at a financial disadvantage to suburban
schools. So far the new taxes and school-spending scheme have
produced an outpouring of bitterness and resentment among
voters who believe they are the plan's losers. In any event,
the Florio philosophy, rooted in sharp class distinctions,
marks a break with the incentive-based economic policies of
the recent past.
   Meanwhile, of course, both New York City and New York
State are well along the path to raising taxes significantly
to pay for their public-sector commitments. Coincidentally,
the New York Times last week carried an article about young
Long Island couples who are increasingly thinking of moving
to Florida, partly to escape their high taxes.
   So far, a string of presidential vetoes by Mr. Bush
suggests he is sensitive to the dangers of loading the
economy at the federal level with more costs. However, the
revenue side of the Washington fiscal equation remains open
for negotiation. If Washington now adds to a tax burden
already building again in economic bellwether states such as
New York, New Jersey and California, voters in elections from
now through 1992 may go looking for politicians and parties
to tag with the blame.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900626-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   Hitachi, Motorola
   Agree to Pursue
   End to Patent Suit
   ----
   By Marilyn Chase
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   MOT HIT
</CO>
<IN>
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Hitachi Ltd. and Motorola Inc., under pressure from a
court deadline this week in their patent squabbles, have
decided to try to work them out on their own.
   The two companies said they have agreed in principle to
discussions aimed at ending a dispute involving the Hitachi
H8/532 microprocessor and the Motorola MC 68030
microprocessor.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This is not a final agreement," a Hitachi spokesman said,
and it isn't expected to bring about a swift resolution of
the 18-month-old litigation. "Hitachi would like to see an
agreement in two to three months," he said.
   Nor would it resolve any of the other intellectual
property and technology disputes in which the two electronic
giants have long been embroiled, the spokesman added.
   A spokeswoman for Motorola, Schaumburg, Ill., said she
couldn't discuss any details of the negotiations.
   "As to what's on the table right now, we can't talk about
any of it," she said.
   The microprocessors at stake in the suit are lucrative
sources of revenue for the combatants.
   Hitachi doesn't sell the H8/532 yet in the U.S. However,
it represents about 1% of Hitachi's world-wide semiconductor
revenues, or $30 million. And Hitachi had counted on
extending its marketing of the H8/532 to the U.S. in the near
future, the spokesman said.
   Motorola's market-leading MC 68030 microprocessor is used
in powerful machines made by Apple Computer Inc. and
Hewlett-Packard Co.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading, Hitachi
closed at $95 a share, down $1.75 from Friday's close.
Motorola closed at $84.125 a share, down $1.875.
   On March 29, a federal court judge ruled that neither
company could manufacture or distribute the disputed products
in the U.S. because each side is infringing, the Hitachi
spokesman said.
   Motorola, for its part, obtained a temporary stay of the
injunction against product sales. Last week, however, a judge
vacated that stay in a setback to Motorola, which promptly
appealed to the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington.
   That stay of judgment is due to expire Friday, increasing
the pressure on both companies to reach a settlement out of
court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0074
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900626-0074.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   China Buffs
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   There is some comfort to the news that China has allowed
the flight into exile of two of its leading dissidents,
astrophysicist Fang Lizhi and his wife, Li Shuxian. Both have
been brave and patriotic advocates of democracy in China.
When the Chinese regime trampled the Tiananmen uprising last
June, Mr. Fang and his wife were forced to take refuge in the
U.S. Embassy in Beijing, where they have lived the past year
under siege. It's likely they'll find life easier in England,
where they reportedly have been granted asylum.
   This silver lining hardly seems reason for the U.S. to
have hailed Mr. Fang's departure as "a humanitarian action"
by China's Communist regime. His release takes place under a
thundercloud of repression that continues to cast its shadow
across the 1.1 billion people of China.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Why must Fang Lizhi and Li Shuxian flee China at all?
Their only "crime" was that their calls for democracy drew a
huge following among China's people. Such bravery remains a
counterrevolutionary crime in China. Indeed, the special
exemption from China's "laws" just granted to the Fangs helps
to underline the arbitrary nature of government in China,
where there is no law other than what suits the Communist
Party's convenience.
   China's regime congratulated itself yesterday via the
official state newswire, Xinhua, for giving "lenient
treatment" to Mr. Fang and his wife. There is no leniency,
however, for champions of Chinese democracy who are less
famous in the West. One of Mr. Fang's precursors, Wei
Jingsheng, remains in prison, serving the 15-year sentence
imposed in 1979 after he published his eloquent essay, "The
Fifth Modernization -- Democracy." Many who took part in last
year's protests also remain in prison, such as student
leaders Wang Dan, if he is still alive, and Liu Xiaobo.
   China's official explanation for Mr. Fang's release
included a reference to Mr. Fang having been allowed to go
abroad for "medical treatment." It's too early to confirm
this explanation. But we do know that what's truly ailing in
China is the centrally planned economy. The Party has chosen
to sacrifice economic growth in favor of tighter state
control over people's daily lives. It hopes to alleviate some
of the pain with foreign money. The decision to let Mr. Fang
leave for "medical treatment" seems well-timed to influence
the imminent annual meeting of the world's seven leading
industrial nations whose agenda will include government loans
to China.
   If the G-7 ministers or President Bush want to create
genuine standards for reform in China, they will have to look
beyond the release of political hostages such as Fang Lizhi.
Real political reform would mean that people such as Messrs.
Fang, Wei, Wang and Liu could live freely in China and
present their democratic arguments to the Chinese people. It
would mean that dissidents could form political parties to
compete with the Communists without fear of being jailed or
shot.
   The sad truth is that even if China were to expel every
dissident the West has ever heard of, such actions would not
necessarily reflect a basic change in the country's
totalitarian system. Mr. Fang's fate this past year became
one of the symbols of repression in China. Freeing only the
symbol tells us mainly that China has so stifled dissent at
home that it can now devote some energy to buffing its public
relations abroad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0073
</DOCNO>
