<HL>
   International:
   Beijing Permits Fang Lizhi to Leave
   U.S. Embassy and Travel to Britain
   ----
   By Adi Ignatius
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   BEIJING -- Chinese authorities allowed dissident Fang
Lizhi to leave his yearlong refuge in the U.S. Embassy and
travel overseas, removing a major irritant in U.S.-China
relations.
   The astrophysicist and outspoken human-rights advocate
left Beijing yesterday with his wife, Li Shuxian, aboard a
U.S. military plane. The couple, who took sanctuary in the
embassy after the brutal suppression of last June's
pro-democracy movement, will resettle in Britain, diplomats
said. He has accepted a post at Cambridge University.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   China's official Xinhua news agency said the pair were
given "lenient treatment" so they could seek medical care
abroad. Chinese and diplomatic sources said Mr. Fang has a
heart ailment.
   The freeing of the couple, accused by Chinese authorities
of "instigating" last spring's demonstrations, may prompt
calls in Washington for improved U.S.-China ties. The Bush
administration has argued that allowing the pair to leave was
a prerequisite for better relations.
   The White House immediately declared, "This humanitarian
action is a far-sighted, significant step that will improve
the atmosphere for progress in our bilateral relations."
Noting that Dr. Fang's second son, who plans to study in the
U.S., is still in China, State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler said, "We have no reason to believe that
the son will have any difficulty obtaining permission to
study abroad."
   The decision to allow the pair to leave doesn't markedly
alter the political situation in China. Hundreds of persons
arrested after the Tiananmen incident have been released from
prison, but hundreds more prisoners of conscience remain,
often without being charged. But the release of Mr. Fang is
sure to bolster President Bush's argument that his China
policy has achieved tangible benefits.
   U.S.-China ties have been icy since June 4, 1989, when
Chinese troops killed hundreds of demonstrators in Beijing.
President Bush curtailed most high-level visits and suspended
military aid and some economic assistance. Washington also
blocked the resumption of normal lending to China from
multilateral agencies.
   The Fang release may have been timed by Beijing to ward
off further sanctions. Congress is preparing to vote --
almost certainly favorably -- on Mr. Bush's recommendation to
retain beneficial trade terms for China. But some lawmakers
have threatened an attempt to make future trade ties with
China dependent on Beijing's human rights record.
   State Department spokeswoman Tutwiler denied
"categorically" that the U.S. and China cut any deals trading
the Fang release for a lifting of U.S. sanctions against
China. Indeed, she said China would have to free other
prisoners and stop jamming the Voice of America if it wants
"a more normal relationship."
   China for months has indicated a willingness to allow the
pair to leave, but only under certain conditions, including
an admission of guilt as well as a guarantee that they
wouldn't engage in anti-China activities overseas. The Xinhua
report hinted at a face-saving compromise: It said the two
dissidents admitted they had opposed the Communist Party's
monopoly on power and ideology, which amounts to a technical
violation of China's constitution.
   Such a statement enables Beijing to maintain that the pair
had repented. At the same time, the pair apparently never
admitted any responsibility for last year's demonstrations,
the core allegation against them. Xinhua also indicated that
the couple agreed that "they will not engage in activities
directed against China after they leave the country."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0057
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900626-0057.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Continues Slide on Low Volume;
   Duty Free International Dives 4 1/4 to 24 3/4
   ----
   By Anne Newman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter stocks tumbled in the wake of Friday's
sell-off of larger, exchange listed shares.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index fell 3.69 to 455.64, a 0.80%
slide, as volume dropped sharply to 113.5 million shares from
167.5 million Friday. Declining shares outpaced advancing
stocks by a wide margin, 1,136 to 765.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It was a very sleepy day, almost like a holiday," said
E.E. "Buzzy" Geduld, president of Herzog, Heine, Geduld, a
major dealer in OTC stocks for other market professionals. "I
suspect it will be this way until after the Fourth of July,"
he added.
   Hank Striefler, OTC trading manager for Shearson Lehman
Hutton, said smaller stocks were hit hard yesterday as the
sell programs that tackled exchange-listed shares Friday
spilled over into the OTC market. However, Mr. Striefler
remained optimistic about the longer-term picture. "I think
we're near a bottom," he said, suggesting that later in the
week portfolio managers may buy smaller stocks to "window
dress" their portfolios.
   Mr. Striefler agreed with Mr. Geduld that selling was
orderly and across all OTC industry groups. He also predicted
that this week will be quiet. "The closer we get to July 4,
{trading} is going to come to a halt," he said.
   Duty Free International plunged 4 1/4 to 24 3/4. Officials
of the Ridgefield, Conn., operator of duty-free stores told
analysts that second-quarter sales at some of its stores
aren't likely to be as strong as expected, according to Dow
Jones Professional Investor Report. Chief financial officer
Gerald F. Egan also said that sales last weekend at some of
its Canadian border stores were lower than expected,
following the collapse of the Meech Lake plan giving Quebec
special status.
   Price Co. jumped 2 to 38 3/4. The San Diego wholesale
cash-and-carry merchandising company reported net income for
the third quarter ended June 10 of 47 cents a share, fully
diluted, up from restated income of 42 cents a share a year
earlier.
   Sun Microsystems added 5/8 to 32 and was one of the few
technology stocks that closed higher. The Mountain View,
Calif., maker of computer workstations said that a unit of
the company renewed a one-year "master purchase agreement"
with Unisys Corp. under which Unisys will resell, and
purchase for internal development, Sun's Sparc-based
workstations and servers.
   Among other technology shares, Intel fell 1/2 to 45 1/2;
Apple Computer lost 1/4 to 41 1/4, and Microsoft slid 1 1/4
to 74 1/2. Microsoft said it's increasing its support staff
by 60 people over the next 12 weeks and inaugurating a
24-hour telephone hotline and other services to assist the
growing number of users of the 3.0 version of its Windows
software. The Redmond, Wash., software maker said sales of
the product outpaced its "most aggressive" sales predictions.
   Henley Group rose 1/4 to 31 1/4 after the La Jolla,
Calif., industrial company said it may sell as much as its
entire 38.5% stake in Itel Corp.
   California Microwave advanced 1/4 to 8 1/4. A favorable
profile of the Sunnyvale, Calif., electronics communications
company appeared in the current issue of Barron's.
   American Medical Electronics jumped 1 1/4 to 12 1/4 after
Rauscher Pierce Refsnes analyst Craig B. Dickson made bullish
comments about the Dallas maker of medical devices for the
third consecutive day, DJPIR reported. Mr. Dickson is
optimistic about the prospects for the company's device to
assist healing after spinal surgery.
   Tele-Communications stumbled 5/8 to 14 after this
newspaper reported that National Broadcasting Co. executives
privately gave little chance of success to a proposal by the
Denver cable company to use its cable systems as NBC
affiliates in rural areas not already served by the network's
affiliates.
   Software Toolworks continued to slide on heavy volume.
After the market closed, investor John R. Purcell of
Stamford, Conn., said he lowered his position in the Sherman
Oaks, Calif. software publisher to 4.3% of its outstanding
common shares.Software Toolworks fell 1/4 to 15 on 1.25
million shares.
   Biogen fell 1 to 21 1/2. Chicago-based analyst Peter F.
Drake of Vector Securities International tied the drop to
profit-taking after last week's AIDS conference in San
Francisco, according to DJPIR. Mr. Drake explained that some
investors had been expecting wider press coverage of data
presented Thursday about the Cambridge, Mass., biotechnology
company's alpha interferon product, which is used in
combination with Burroughs-Wellcome's AZT drug to treat
people who test positive for the AIDS virus but who don't yet
have symptoms. Biogen climbed as high as 23 in advance of the
conference.
   Tyson Foods dropped 1 1/4 to 31 1/2. This newspaper's
"Heard on the Street" column questioned not only why the
poultry producer recently changed its depreciation schedule,
but also whether a potential cyclical downturn in poultry
prices will affect Springdale, Ark., company's ability to
digest the $1.3 billion of long-term debt it absorbed in the
acquisition of Holly Farms.
   Liz Claiborne slipped 1 3/4 to 30 1/4. The North Bergen,
N.J., apparel maker appeared in a USA Today list of companies
reporting insider selling, with four Liz Claiborne insiders
recently selling 804,000 shares of stock.
</TEXT>
