<HL>
   Business Brief -- Occidental Petroleum Corp.:
   Estimate of Oil Reserves
   In North Sea Field Lifted
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C20
</SO>
<CO>
   OXY
</CO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
OIL, SECONDARY (OIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Occidental Petroleum (Caledonia) Ltd., a London unit of
Los Angeles-based Occidental Petroleum Corp., said a
step-out, or appraisal, well in the Saltire field in the
North Sea indicates the field's estimated recoverable oil
reserves are 30% greater than formerly believed, or about 130
million barrels.
   Previously, the field's recoverable reserves of
high-quality oil were estimated at 100 million barrels.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Occidental said the appraisal well had flows at stabilized
daily rates of 9,635 barrels of oil and 13 million cubic feet
of gas.
   The Occidental unit said the test-well results also
indicate that the Saltire field, about 120 miles northeast of
Aberdeen, Scotland, is larger than previously believed. As a
result, the company will seek Britain's approval to develop
the field, starting next fall, at an estimated cost of $600
million. Production is expected to begin in the second half
of 1992. Occidental is the well operator and holds a 36.5%
interest in it.
</TEXT>
