<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   U.S. Issues
   Payout Rules
   For Thrifts
   ----
   By Paul Duke Jr.
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
DIVIDENDS (DIV)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Office of Thrift Supervision issued
rules spelling out how much thrifts can pay in dividends, a
move that OTS Director Timothy Ryan said was intended to make
thrifts more attractive to buyers and investors.
   Mr. Ryan also said he intends to issue a policy in the
next several days outlining when the OTS will disclose
administrative charges brought by the agency against thrift
executives. The decision could affect whether the thrift
office airs its case against Neil Bush, the president's son,
regarding his actions as a director of a failed Colorado
thrift.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Under the dividend policy, thrifts that currently meet
capital standards that are due to take effect in 1995 can pay
all their net income and half their surplus capital -- or
capital in excess of the 1995 requirements -- in dividends.
Thrifts that meet current capital standards but not the 1995
standard can pay dividends totaling 25% to 75% of their net,
depending on how close they are to the 1995 requirement.
Thrifts that fall below current capital requirements can't
pay dividends without specific approval from the OTS.
   About 1,200 thrifts with $215 billion in assets, or 20% of
the industry's total assets, currently meet the 1995 capital
requirements. The new policy takes the place of a complicated
mix of regulations under which undercapitalized thrifts
generally weren't allowed to pay dividends. In the past,
applications by thrifts to pay dividends were often handled
on a case-by-case basis.
   Mr. Ryan said the policy was intended to make it clear to
investors that they can get a return through dividends. "We
need to provide for thrifts to increase capital, but we also
need to provide some attractiveness to investors," he said.
"The value of the thrift charter is very much in question,"
he added, referring to the reluctance of investors to buy the
hundreds of insolvent thrifts the government is selling off.
Buyers of insolvent thrifts are required to bring them into
compliance with capital standards.
   The OTS also said it plans this week to propose relaxing,
during a transitional period, limits on the size of loans
thrifts can make to an individual borrower. Last year's
thrift-bailout law limited loans to an individual borrower to
15% of the thrift's capital. Previously, the limit was 100%
of capital. The restriction has sparked controversy in the
real estate industry, where many say it has forced lenders to
turn down economically viable projects.
   Mr. Ryan also said he is working on a policy governing
when the OTS will announce administrative charges brought
against thrift executives. Currently, final judgments against
individuals are announced, but regulators don't announce
charges, for fear of the possible effects on a thrift. In the
case of failed thrifts, Mr. Ryan said, that wouldn't be a
consideration.
   Some congressional Democrats have pushed for the OTS to
announce details of its conflict-of-interest charges against
Neil Bush, who was a director of Silverado Banking, Savings &amp;
Loan Association in Denver. Mr. Bush has denied any
wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900626-0020
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900626-0020.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   House-Senate Panel
   Clears Bill to Protect
   Handicapped People
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- House and Senate conferees approved
legislation that would bar discrimination against handicapped
individuals on a broad front, including public accommodations
and employment.
   The bill was approved by wide margins in both chambers,
and if the conference version passes the House and Senate, it
is expected to be signed by President Bush. Known as the
Americans with Disabilities Act, the measure would extend to
about 43 million disabled persons the kind of protection
against discrimination now afforded by a patchwork of state
and local rules and in requirements for federal contractors
and grant recipients.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The conferees killed an amendment in the House bill that
specified that food companies could transfer workers with
contagious diseases to jobs that didn't involve handling
food. The amendment dealt with employer concerns about
employees with acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Senate conferees ignored a nonbinding resolution passed by
the Senate, instructing them to accede to the House
amendment. They quoted Health and Human Services Secretary
Louis Sullivan that the AIDS-causing virus cannot be
transmitted by handling food and that an amendment based on
public "fears and misconceptions" would only complicate
efforts to control the disease.
   The Senate conferees also noted that both the bill and
existing law already allow employers to transfer or fire
workers who pose a direct threat to the health and safety of
others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
