<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions June 26-July 9
</HL>
<DATE>
06/26/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   New York Public Library: "Portugal-Brazil: The Age of
Atlantic Discoveries" -- More than 150 items -- navigational
instruments, rare books and letters, early maps, original
15th- and 16th-century prints, oil paintings and illuminated
manuscripts -- documenting Portugal's seafaring ways and the
encounter of Portuguese and Brazilian cultures in the 16th
century. Highlights include the Treaty of Tordesillas (1494),
which drew a dividing line in the Atlantic Ocean granting
Portugal all land to the east of the line and Spain all land
to the west; a letter dated May 1, 1500, to Dom Manuel of
Portugal relaying the first news to Europe about Brazil; and
the first edition of Sir Thomas More's "Utopia" (1516), which
was heavily influenced by written accounts of Portuguese
discoveries. Fifth Avenue and 42nd Street, through Sept. 1.
                                                                                                       

   Arthur M. Sackler Gallery, Smithsonian Institution,
Washington, D.C.: "Yokohama: Prints From Nineteenth-Century
Japan" -- Eighty-five color woodblock prints tracing the
development of the city of Yokohama from 1860 to 1890, the
period in which the feudal structure collapsed and imperial
power was re-established under the Emperor Meiji. Of special
interest are those that depict foreign ships arriving in
Yokohama harbor; images of foreigners that show a Japanese
fascination with Western clothing and furnishings; and prints
intended to help Japanese pronounce words in English and
other languages. Through Sept. 9. The exhibition then travels
to the Asian Art Museum of San Francisco (Oct. 10-Dec. 9),
and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art (Jan. 10-March 10,
1991).
                                                                                                       

   Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts, Philadelphia:
"Sculptures by Duane Hanson" -- Seventeen life-size and
extraordinarily lifelike polyvinyl people sculptures created
by this Minnesota-born artist. Among others, you'll meet a
tired, beer-bellied traveler leaning on his bags, a couple of
older folks seated at a luncheonette table, and two portly
tourists loaded down with cameras. Broad and Cherry Streets,
through Sept. 23.
                                                                                                       

   FESTIVAL
                                                                                                       

   Caramoor Music Festival, Katonah, N.Y., presents nine
weeks of music on the Caramoor estate. Highlights of the
event, in its 45th season, are: a rare performance of Robert
Schumann's "Scenes From Goethe's `Faust'; world premieres by
Nikolai Karetnikov and William Schimmel; a Fourth of July
salute to Broadway composers; a mini J.S. Bach festival; and
jazz from the Count Basie Orchestra. Through Aug. 19. (914)
232-1252.
                                                                                                       

   Colorado Music Festival, Boulder, celebrates its 14th
season with 30 symphony-orchestra, chamber-orchestra and
chamber-music/recital performances. Music director Giora
Berstein and the 80-member Colorado Festival Orchestra will
be joined by such guest artists as conductors Alun Francis
and Antoni Wit; violinist Miriam Fried; and pianists
Christopher O'Riley and Grant Johannesen. Among the special
programs are a Sunday-evening Classic Series featuring the
works of Schubert, Mozart, Haydn and Bach; and a
Tuesday-evening Celebrity Series showcasing artists and
ensembles in solo recital and chamber-music concerts. Most
performances at Chautauqua Auditorium, 900 Baseline Road.
Through Aug. 3. (303) 449-2413.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Lyric Opera of Cleveland kicks off its Al Fresco Festival
season with performances of Rossini's "Cinderella." Joyce
Campana sings the title role; Donald Sherrill is Don
Magnifico, Cinderella's stepfather; and Fred Love and Howard
Carr portray the servant and prince, respectively. Stephen
Sulich conducts. June 26, 28 and 30. Also on the schedule:
Jerry Bock and Sheldon Harnick's "She Loves Me," with Michael
Milton and Nancy Hudson as secret pen pals Georg and Amalia
(July 12, 14, 17, 19 and 21); and Mozart's "The Magic Flute"
(Aug. 2, 4, 7, 9, 10 and 11). Cleveland Institute of Music,
11021 East Boulevard, University Circle. (216) 231-2910.
</TEXT>
